<!--
VOICING PLAN — In The Bleak MidWinter (F major, 4/4):

Phrase 1 (mm. pickup–4): Lighter opening. Pickup and M1 use vi7 (Dm7) as the
tonal center — the hymn opens in a modal Dorian feel on D. RH uses 2-note
inner voices (10ths/3rds), LH carries open-fifth "334" voicings. M2 introduces
IV and V with open spacing. M4 (Gm whole note) is the first full sustained voicing.

Phrase 2 (mm. 5–8): Reprise of the opening melodic phrase. Same harmonic outline
(vi7→IV→vi→I) but the LH in M6 widens to a full Dm7 "333" chord. M8 cadences
on vi→I using a dotted-half in both hands, creating a long breath before the
contrasting section.

Phrase 3 (mm. 9–12): Climax. Melody rises to D5 in M10. IV→I oscillation with
full "334" LH voicings (4 notes each). RH moves in contrary motion to LH. M12
is a full V (C major) whole-note preparation for the final verse.

Phrase 4 (mm. 13–15): Final verse. M13 restates the opening texture. M14 is
Gm→Dm7 with sustaining LH open-5th chords. M15 ends on C→E° (half cadence
on vii°), matching the source ABC's open right barline — this is a partial
final bar.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- M1→M2: RH C5→Bb4 (step down) into IV. LH D3→G2 (P4 down) root motion.
- M7: C→Dm→E° line — bass descends C3→D3→E3 (stepwise). Against this the
  RH rises E4→F4→E4 creating a neighbor motion around E.
- M11: Full descending 6th-chord progression (I–iii–ii–I) with chromatic
  inner-voice flow C→A→G→F in the melody and matching thirds in the LH.
- M12: Half cadence has a 4-3 suspension in the RH (G4→E4) creating a
  brief dissonance that resolves to the final chord.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Opens (pickup–M2): 2–3 harp notes, open register, light.
- Builds (M3–M6): 3 notes RH + 3–4 notes LH, rhythmic variety introduced.
- Climax (M9–M10): Reaches full 4-note LH + 2-note RH. Melody at D5.
- Close (M12–M15): Returns to 3-note LH voicings. Final vii° leaves open.
-->
